{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17591863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17591863"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:07:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:07:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15212"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15212"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.45,0.21,0.07,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8572"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21320"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man is being treated for a squamous cell carcinoma of the oesophagus. Part of this treatment will be external beam radiation therapy to the mid-thoracic region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe radiotherapy in itself could have complications related to the field of irradiation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common acute complication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myelopathy","Oesophagitis","Pericardial effusion","Pneumonitis","Skin ulceration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERadiation therapy to the thoracic region commonly causes several complications, with the timing and severity depending on the total dose, fractionation schedule, and volume of tissue irradiated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common acute complication, typically developing 2-3 weeks into treatment. \u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is usually a subacute complication occurring 1-6 months after treatment. \u003Cstrong\u003EPericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare late complication that may develop months to years after therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003EMyelopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious late complication that can occur months to years after treatment. \u003Cstrong\u003ESkin ulceration\u003C/strong\u003E is uncommon with modern radiation techniques due to skin-sparing approaches.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radiation therapy can cause both acute and late toxicity to surrounding tissues including mucositis, dermatitis, and organ-specific damage","The complications of radiation therapy depend on the anatomical location being treated and the radiation dose/field size"],"references":["Wang Y, Mukkamalla SKR, Singh R, Babiker HM, Lyons S. Esophageal Cancer. 2024 Aug 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083661","Codipilly DC, Wang KK. Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the Esophagus. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2022 Sep;51(3):457-484. doi: 10.1016/j.gtc.2022.06.005. Epub 2022 Aug 29. PMID: 36153105","Hadian Y, Howell JY, Ramsey ML, et al. Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma. [Updated 2024 Jul 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441939/","Burton KA, Ashack KA, Khachemoune A. Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma: A Review of High-Risk and Metastatic Disease. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2016 Oct;17(5):491-508. doi: 10.1007/s40257-016-0207-3. PMID: 27358187","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15212"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52053"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T14:56:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T14:56:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7903"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66600"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student"